## R Markdown Introduction 

R Markdown is a tool that allows you to combine written text, R code, and output such as tables and graphs into a single document. This makes it useful for creating reproducible reports in data analysis.

## Narrative Paragraph 
I am learning how to use R Markdown to organize my work. Instead of writing code separately from my report, I can include everything in one place. This makes my work clearer and simple to understand.


When you click the **Knit** button a document will be generated that includes both content as well as the output of any embedded R code chunks within the document. You can embed an R code chunk like this:

```{r cars}
data(cars)

summary(cars)
```

## Including Plots

You can also embed plots, for example:

```{r pressure, echo=FALSE}
plot(cars$speed, cars$dist,
     main = "Speed vs Stopping Distance",
     xlab = "Speed",
     ylab = "Stopping Distance")
plot(pressure)
```

Note that the `echo = FALSE` parameter was added to the code chunk to prevent printing of the R code that generated the plot.
